Java’s `String.indexOf(String needle)` uses a **naive substring search algorithm**.  
It scans the haystack character by character until it finds the target substring or concludes it doesn’t exist.

---

## Simplified Internal Logic (based on OpenJDK source)

```java
public int indexOf(String str, int fromIndex) {
    char[] value = this.value;      // haystack characters
    char[] target = str.value;      // needle characters
    int targetCount = str.length();

    int max = value.length - targetCount;

    for (int i = fromIndex; i <= max; i++) {
        int j = 0;
        while (j < targetCount && value[i + j] == target[j]) {
            j++;
        }
        if (j == targetCount) {
            return i; // match found
        }
    }
    return -1; // not found
}

Step-by-Step Description
Step 1: Loop over haystack
Iterate from fromIndex to n - m.

At each position, check if the substring starting at i matches the needle.

Step 2: Character comparison
Compare haystack and needle characters one by one.

If all characters match, return the starting index.

Step 3: Mismatch handling
If mismatch occurs, move to the next position in haystack.

Continue until either a match is found or the end is reached.

Step 4: Return value
If match found → return starting index.

If no match → return -1.

Complexity
Worst case: O(n · m)
For each of the (n - m + 1) positions, up to m comparisons.

Best case: O(m) if the substring is found at the start.

Space: O(1) (just counters and comparisons).

Example
java
String haystack = "mississippi";
String needle = "issip";

System.out.println(haystack.indexOf(needle)); // Output: 4
At index 4, "issip" matches exactly.
